00:00:43.848 --> 00:00:46.179
FINDING THE BEST INSURER

00:00:46.204 --> 00:00:49.809
In India, there are approximately 30 or 35 health insurance companies.

00:00:49.834 --> 00:00:50.826
Not all of them are good.

00:00:50.851 --> 00:00:53.179
But we need to know how to find a good one.

00:00:53.204 --> 00:00:56.191
For that, first we will have to find the 'incurred claims ratio'.

00:00:56.191 --> 00:00:58.224
This means amount of claims paid...

00:00:58.249 --> 00:01:01.512
divided by total amount of premiums earned in one year.

00:01:01.537 --> 00:01:03.054
That's how Insurance businesses work.

00:01:03.079 --> 00:01:07.185
The companies collects premiums from a lot of people.

00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:10.715
Hoping that everyone doesn't claim it together in a single year.

00:01:10.715 --> 00:01:12.844
So the companies incurred claims ratio states that.

00:01:12.844 --> 00:01:15.016
How much money did the company earn through premiums and...

00:01:15.016 --> 00:01:18.245
how much percentage of the money was distributed through claims?

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:19.975
If the percentage is very low...

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.320
that means the company is not passing the claims easily.

00:01:23.345 --> 00:01:25.760
And it will further be reflected on it's complaints data.

00:01:25.785 --> 00:01:28.818
And If this percentage is more than 100%.

00:01:28.843 --> 00:01:32.480
That means, the company is spending more on claims than it earns.

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:34.668
So where is this extra money coming from?

00:01:34.693 --> 00:01:38.286
Who will fund a loss-making company, and when will it be funded?

00:01:38.311 --> 00:01:41.892
The healthy incurred claims ratio is somewhere around 80-85%.

00:01:41.917 --> 00:01:44.681
And there are several companies which I have marked green.

00:01:44.706 --> 00:01:48.843
The ICR and its average for the past three years have been mentioned here.

00:01:48.868 --> 00:01:50.253
And If you look at it carefully,

00:01:50.253 --> 00:01:54.501
then such companies whose incurred claims ratio is more than 100%.

00:01:54.526 --> 00:01:56.964
All of those are public insurance companies.

00:01:56.989 --> 00:01:58.640
If you want to study ICR further.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:02.735
There is a segment-wise data of the past 10 years in the IRDA's handbook.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:03.908
You won't have to do so much.

00:02:03.908 --> 00:02:05.644
But you can find certain interesting things here.

00:02:05.669 --> 00:02:08.210
This data is from 2014 - 2024.

00:02:08.210 --> 00:02:11.499
I have only highlighted the last data. I haven't focused on the past 9 years.

00:02:11.524 --> 00:02:13.529
In this, the ICR is shown in four segments.

00:02:13.529 --> 00:02:15.720
And the total is also mentioned in the end.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:21.020
Your total incurred claims ratio will not match with your IRDAI's annual report.

00:02:21.045 --> 00:02:22.284
And it won't because...

00:02:22.309 --> 00:02:24.976
The granular data of the IRDAI's handbook...

00:02:25.001 --> 00:02:29.120
you will only get the health insurance data without personal accident and travel.

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:30.560
How do we make sense of this data?

00:02:30.585 --> 00:02:34.592
Firstly we will see, which company is close to 80-85%.

00:02:34.617 --> 00:02:37.921
For example, Chola Mandalam is at 81% in total.

00:02:37.921 --> 00:02:41.687
But as soon as I check the individual policies, then this is 360%.

00:02:41.687 --> 00:02:47.393
i.e. the premium they earn from individual policies, they pay 360% in claims.

00:02:47.393 --> 00:02:49.177
And that's a loss-making business.

00:02:49.177 --> 00:02:53.160
If you look at the family floater of this company ICR, then it's only 14%.

00:02:53.185 --> 00:02:55.289
It means, they are not passing the claim here.

00:02:55.314 --> 00:02:56.960
There is something weird happening here.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:59.960
Next we will head to the complaints data.

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:04.243
This is the number of complaints per 10,000 claims &amp; industry average is 22.

